<paper id="1582538828"><title>Zero-Knowledge Proofs for Finite Field Arithmetic; or: Can Zero-Knowledge be for Free?</title><year>1998</year><authors><author org="ETH Zürich" id="2156861640">Ronald Cramer</author><author org="Aarhus University," id="2682364181">Ivan Damgård</author></authors><n_citation>60</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1484557542</reference><reference>1524288918</reference><reference>1538463291</reference><reference>1539572409</reference><reference>1557783852</reference><reference>1850675439</reference><reference>1885156594</reference><reference>1970606468</reference><reference>1996888795</reference><reference>2036133214</reference><reference>2053086236</reference><reference>2080123784</reference><reference>2095708839</reference><reference>2099000090</reference><reference>2102632861</reference><reference>2108834246</reference><reference>2120551550</reference><reference>2151433956</reference><reference>2156186849</reference><reference>2176018476</reference><reference>2293988196</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0055745</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.55751">Prime (order theory)</keyword><keyword weight="0.46678">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.52117">Polynomial</keyword><keyword weight="0.46767">Algebra</keyword><keyword weight="0.49355">Interactive proof system</keyword><keyword weight="0.56154">Multiplicative function</keyword><keyword weight="0.55962">Commitment scheme</keyword><keyword weight="0.4475">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.55624">Finite field arithmetic</keyword><keyword weight="0.50278">Zero-knowledge proof</keyword><keyword weight="0.4426">Mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.52673">Discrete logarithm</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present a general method for constructing commitment schemes based on existence of q-one way group homomorphisms, in which elements in a finite prime field GF(q) can be committed to. A receiver of commitments can non-interactively check whether committed values satisfy linear equations. Multiplicative relations can be verified interactively with exponentially small error, while communicating only a constant number of commitments. Particular assumptions sufficient for our commitment schemes include: the RSA assumption, hardness of discrete log in a prime order group, and polynomial security of Diffie-Hellman encryption.</abstract></paper>